title: Where to watch Sundaya s rare a supermoona lunar eclipse - Press-Telegram
text:
That's because the 72-minute lunar eclipse, which falls during the harvest moon, starts at 6:07 p.m., but the sun isn't expected to set until 6:43 p.m. As the moon rises in the east, it will already be partially eclipsed and will appear reddish. The last supermoon lunar eclipse was more than three decades ago, and the next one will be in 18 years.
 Press-Telegram.
